LAYER 1: ML Frameworks — "The ML Engineer's Workshop"
Amazon SageMaker AI
What it is: A complete platform to build, train, and deploy your own ML models from scratch.
Backend analogy:
Like setting up your own Kubernetes cluster to run custom microservices. Full control, but you manage everything.
What you do here:
Write training code in Python (PyTorch, TensorFlow)
Provision GPU instances
Train models on your data
Deploy as endpoints
Monitor performance
Who uses this:
ML Engineers
Data Scientists
Researchers training custom models
🎯 Will YOU use this?
Rarely. As an Agentic AI Engineer, you'll mostly use pre-trained models. But good to know it exists for when you need custom training.
🔧 LAYER 2: AI/ML Services — "The API Toolbox"
These are pre-built, managed services you call via API. Think of them like AWS-hosted microservices that do one specific AI task well.
Quick Tour of Each Service

LAYER 3: GENERATIVE AI — "YOUR HOME BASE" ⭐
This is where you'll spend 90% of your time as an Agentic AI Engineer.
1. Amazon SageMaker JumpStart
What it is: A hub of pre-trained foundation models you can deploy with one click.
Backend analogy:
Like a package manager (npm) for AI models. Browse, select, deploy.
What's inside:
Hundreds of open-source models (Llama, Mistral, Stable Diffusion)
Ready-to-deploy endpoints
Fine-tuning templates
When to use:
You want an open-source model (not Claude/GPT)
You need full control over the model
You want to fine-tune on your own infrastructure
2. Amazon Bedrock ⭐⭐⭐ (MOST IMPORTANT FOR YOU)
What it is: A single API to access foundation models from multiple providers (Anthropic, Meta, Mistral, Amazon, etc.).

